Title: Police victims and their lawyer and family at the LA Press Club, 1967.
Description.caption: PROTESTERS - Interviewed by newsmen were these protesters of police action in breaking up peace marchers during the President's visit. From left, Steven Sokol, who charged he was a victim of police brutality; Philip Chronis, attorney, American Civil Liberties Union member; George Slaff, head of Southern California ACLU; Dr. mortimer Roth, a dentist, with son marc, 11, standing, both listed as victims, and Aris Agnagnos, a member of the board of directors of the ACLU.  Meanwhile, a city councilman demanded a full-scale investigation.
Description.note: Image accompanied by caption is 236643-19-1.|~|The allegations of brutality stem from Pres. Johnson's visit to Century Plaza and the attendant demonstration.

Title: Bishop Asaiah comforts one of the sisters of Fountain of the World at a prayer meeting in comemoration of the bombing that killed sect leader Krishna Venta along with nine others, 1958.
Description.caption: ALL IS FORGIVEN - Bishop Asaiah, who said the sect asks forgiveness for architect of the searing blast, comforts one of sisters at prayer meeting.
Description.note: A bomb set by two ex-members of the sect destroyed their headquarters in Box Canyon, near Chatsworth and Simi Valley.

Description.note: Building was destroyed when a bomb detonated in the groups home in Box Canyon, near Chatsworth and Simi Valley.

Title: Mother Ruth, widow of Krishna Venta, reunites with two of her daughters at Los Angeles International Airport, 1958.
Description.caption: Daily Mirror caption: WIDOW OF SLAIN LEADER OF RELIGIOUS CULT ARRIVES FROM ALASKA - Mother Ruth is greeted at airport by two of her daughters, Lael, 8, and Sharva, 11.|~|LA Times caption: VENTA'S WIDOW ARRIVES - Mother Ruth, widow of Cult Leader Krishna Venta, is greeted by two of her daughters, Lael, 8, and Sharva, 11, as she arrives at Los Angeles International Airport from group's colony in Alaska.
Description.note: Mother Ruth came from Alaska on the occasion of the bombing of Fountain of the World headquarters in Box Canyon, near Chatsworth and Simi Valley, where her husband, Krishna Venta, and others were killed.

Title: Priest Mary Meyer, center, holds picture of slain Krishna Venta. Flanking her are Bishop Nekona, left, and Bishop Asaiah, who temporarily assumed leadership of Fountain of the World after the leader was killed, 1958.
Description.caption: REVEALS RIVALRY - Priest Mary Meyer, center, holds picture of slain Krishna Venta as she tells of intense rivalry between the cult leader and two men who died with him in bombing of monastery.  Flanking her are Bishop Nekona, left, and Bishop Asaiah, who temporarily assumed cult's leadership.
Description.note: Krishna Venta was killed in a bombing of the group's headquarters in Box Canyon, near Chatsworth and Simi Valley.|~|Image that accompanies caption in print is 114115s-2, which was not scanned as of October 17, 2008.

Title: Mugshot of Ralph Muller and portrait of Peter Kamenoff, the two men suspected of bombing the Fountain of the World headquarters. A. 1958.
Description.caption: OUSTED - Peter Kamenoff (Elzibah) was banned from colony by leader.|~|RIVAL LEADER - Ralph Muller (Jeroham) tried to form his own group.
Description.note: The bombing, in Box Canyon, near Chatsworth and Simi Valley, killed the group's leader, Krishna Venta, and nine other followers, including children.  Kamenoff and Muller were former members of the sect and also killed in the blast.

Title: Funeral at Utter-McKinley's North Hollywood Chapel for Krishna Venta and two others, 1958.
Description.caption: CULTISTS' FUNERAL - Priestesses Mary and Wally and Mother Ruth, from left in front row, attend funeral rites for their leader, Krishna Venta, and two others who died in sect bombing.  Mrs. Amelia Baker, sobbing, is comforted by former daughter-in-law, Mrs. Joan Baker, Husband Charles Baker is at right.
Description.note: Krishna Venta and others died in the bombing of the headquarters of Fountain of the World in Box Canyon, near Chatsworth and Simi Valley.

Title: Daniel Ritchie, executive vice president-finance of MCA sits during an interview with himself and President/CEO Lew Wasserman. A. 1969.
Description.caption: WASSERMAN MOODS - Lew Wasserman, president and chief executive of MCA Inc., which owns Decca Records and Universal Pictures, is pushing diversification of MCA, despite fact the company has agreed to sell to Westinghouse Electric.  Daniel Richie, executive vice president-finance, with Wasserman, lower left, is a chief factor in diversification program, wgich includes a savings and loan in Colorado.

Title: Lew Wasserman being interviewed by Arelo Sederberg. H. 1969.
Description.caption: WASSERMAN MOODS - Lew Wasserman, president and chief executive of MCA Inc., which owns Decca Records and Universal Pictures, is pushing diversification of MCA, despite fact the company has agreed to sell to Westinghouse Electric. Title: Hugh Hefner (left), Mayor Tom Bradley (center) and Los Angeles Times Publisher Otis Chandler at reception for Freedom of Press exhibit, Los Angeles, 1980
Description.caption: A LOOK AT FREEDOM  Mayor Bradley, Times Publisher Otis Chandler and Hugh Hefner of Playboy view documents at reception for the Freedom of Press exhibit on the fifth floor of the Times Building.  The exhibit will be open to the public Tuesday through March 14.  It includes 15 historical papers, four from the trial of John Peter Zenger.  The collection was borrowed from the Chicago Public Library by the Playboy Foundation, sponsor of the exhibit.
Description.note: Image that accompanies caption in print is b1134_291594-17a.  Image has not been scanned as of November 12, 2008.

Description.caption: LOSES FATHER  Diane Carol Harris, 5 , of 7260 Bellaire Ave.,  North Hollywood, is treated for broken arm at Van Nuys Receiving Hospital.  Father, Harley S. Harris, was killed, while mother was among injured.

Description.note: Plane crashed in the Santa Susana Mountains near Simi Valley and Chatsworth.

Title: Passenger cabin of crashed Standard Airlines C-46, 1949.
Description.caption: CLOSE-UP  Wreckage of Standard Airlines C-46 lies on side of steep canyon in Santa Susana Mountains, surrounded by dead and injured, as rescue work begins.  Picture shows how whole section of passenger cabin was sheared away, hurling burned and mangled bodies among boulders 30 yards away.  Another plane reported tragedy.
Description.note: The plane crashed in the Santa Susana mountains, near Chatsworth and Simi Valley.

Title: Rescue workers and survivors stand looking at the wreckage of Standard Airlines C-46, 1949.
Description.caption: BODIES SCATTERED  The dead, dying and injured were flung through the inferno like dolls when Standard Airlines plane crashed in Santa Susana Mountains.  First rescuers from the Simi area raced among the screaming victims, passing by the dead in frantic efforts to save living.  Girls body was found under wing.
Description.note: Plane crashed in Santa Susana Mountains near Simi Valley and Chatsworth.

Title: Krishna Venta (left) and Brother Paul of Fountain of the World Sect give aid in carrying one of the plane crash victims to ambulance, 1949.
Description.caption: SAMARITANS  Krishna Venta, left, self-styled Christ who maintains a monastery in a stone house near crash scene, and Brother Paul, one of his disciples, give aid in carrying one of the victims to ambulance.  They also helped search for dead.
Description.note: The plane, a Standard Airlines C-46, crashed in the Santa Susana Mountains near Chatsworth and Simi Valley.

Title: Aerial photograph of crashed Standard Airlines C-46, 1949.
Description.caption: OVER HEAD  Aerial photo made from less than 1000 feet shows torn hulk of the plane lying on a hillside while rescue parties make their way to the scene.  Plane was bound for Lockheed Air Terminal at Burbank when the crash occurred.
Description.note: Plane crashed in Santa Susana Mountains near Chatsworth and Simi Valley.

Title: Caren Marsh, in hospital, recovers from plane crash, 1949.
Description.caption: CONDITION VERY GOOD  Actress Caren Marsh, recovering from injuries and shock suffered in a plane crash that killed 35 persons Tuesday, declares fight between two passengers couldnt possibly have had anything to do with the crash itself.
Description.note: The plane, a Standard Airlines C-46 crashed in the Santa Susana Mountains near Chatsworth and Simi Valley.
